1
00:00:04,850 --> 00:00:10,550
If we are interested in looking at the relationship between two quantitative variables,

2
00:00:10,550 --> 00:00:13,480
the go-to plot type is the scatter plot.

3
00:00:13,480 --> 00:00:17,940
In a scatter plot, the values of one variable are indicated by position on

4
00:00:17,940 --> 00:00:24,045
the x-axis and values of the other variable are indicated by position on the y-axis.

5
00:00:24,045 --> 00:00:26,800
One point is plotted for every observation we

6
00:00:26,800 --> 00:00:29,940
have in our data resulting in a cloud of points.

7
00:00:29,940 --> 00:00:32,610
The pattern of points can clearly show what kind of

8
00:00:32,610 --> 00:00:36,800
relationship exists between our two variables and its strength.

9
00:00:36,800 --> 00:00:40,370
We are often interested in quantifying the strength of

10
00:00:40,370 --> 00:00:44,755
the relationship between two variables through a correlation coefficient.

11
00:00:44,755 --> 00:00:48,945
The most commonly used measure is the Pearson correlation coefficient,

12
00:00:48,945 --> 00:00:53,520
identified by the letter r. A detailed discussion of

13
00:00:53,520 --> 00:00:56,030
this correlation coefficient is best left for

14
00:00:56,030 --> 00:00:59,970
a different course but a quick overview is worthwhile here.

15
00:00:59,970 --> 00:01:04,160
The statistic takes a value between negative one and one.

16
00:01:04,160 --> 00:01:07,950
Positive numbers indicate relationship where positive changes in

17
00:01:07,950 --> 00:01:11,910
one variable are associated with positive changes in the second.

18
00:01:11,910 --> 00:01:15,680
While negative numbers indicate that when one variable increases,

19
00:01:15,680 --> 00:01:18,640
the second variable tends to decrease.

20
00:01:18,640 --> 00:01:23,540
Values close to the extremes of negative one or one indicate a stronger,

21
00:01:23,540 --> 00:01:29,755
more predictable relationship while values close to zero indicate a weaker relationship.

22
00:01:29,755 --> 00:01:33,410
The correlation coefficient does not necessarily tell you anything

23
00:01:33,410 --> 00:01:37,340
about the steepness of a line that models the relationship.

24
00:01:37,340 --> 00:01:39,275
And most importantly,

25
00:01:39,275 --> 00:01:44,340
the Pearson correlation coefficient only captures linear relationships.

26
00:01:44,340 --> 00:01:47,380
As observed with Anscombe's quartet,

27
00:01:47,380 --> 00:01:51,740
we had multiple data sets with the same Pearson correlation coefficient,

28
00:01:51,740 --> 00:01:56,250
but when plotted demonstrated very different shape characteristics.

29
00:01:56,250 --> 00:01:58,840
It is important to consider not just the numbers

30
00:01:58,840 --> 00:02:02,885
alone but whether or not they are meaningful for your data.

31
00:02:02,885 --> 00:02:07,045
If one of our goals is to create a regression model around the data,

32
00:02:07,045 --> 00:02:10,650
scale transformations can be useful to change a non-linear trend in

33
00:02:10,650 --> 00:02:14,830
the natural units into a linear trend in the transformed units.

34
00:02:14,830 --> 00:02:18,665
Let's say that we have a scatter plot like the one shown.

35
00:02:18,665 --> 00:02:21,265
As we increase the value of x,

36
00:02:21,265 --> 00:02:24,840
the spread in the value of y increases drastically.

37
00:02:24,840 --> 00:02:28,610
If we change the scaling of the y variable to a log scale,

38
00:02:28,610 --> 00:02:30,815
then a linear pattern appears.

39
00:02:30,815 --> 00:02:33,915
This informs us that we want to try using the value of

40
00:02:33,915 --> 00:02:38,180
x to predict the log of y in a regression approach.

